         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">11/12/61 ¶ My dear Sir ¶  ¶ I have much pleasure in sending the meat bisquits &amp; the seeds of useful plants intended for the expedition and of which Dr Murray will take charge. ¶ Regardfully ¶  ¶ yours...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">61.12.11</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Alfred Howitt</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">MS 13071 Royal Society of Victoria Exploration Committee records, box 2078/2, La Trobe Australian Manuscripts Collection, State Library of Victoria, Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS black-edged, M's sister Bertha Doughty died on 7 September 1861. Annotated: ‘Ferdd. Mueller Botanic Garden 11th Decr 1861 | Collection of Seeds’.</p>
               </note>11/12/61</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have much pleasure in sending the meat bisquits &amp; the seeds of useful plants intended for the expedition and of which Dr Murray will take charge.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">The 1861-2 expedition led by Howitt, to collect the bodies of Robert O'Hara Burke and William J. Wills from Coopers Creek, left Melbourne on 9 December 1861 without a surgeon; James Murray left on 12 December to join the expedition in that role (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">Herald</seg> (Melbourne), 24 December 1861, p. 2).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>yours</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">List of seeds forwarded to Mr Howitt.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">The list is on a separate page in an unknown hand; the final paragraph has been added by M.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Sorghum%20sacharatum">Sorghum sacharatum</name>. excellent quickly growing grass affording abundance of food to horses &amp; cattle.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Sorghum%20nigrum">Sorghum nigrum</name> similar to the above but the stalks do not contain so much sacharine matter. The seeds of both kinds are very nutritious. To be sown if possible on a rich soil.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Rumex%20vesicarius">Rumex vesicarius</name> an annual quickly growing antiscorbutic source<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">antiscorbutic source <seg style="font-style: italic; ">insertion by M</seg>.</p>
               </note> plant, the leaves of which serve as spinach. Does very well on sandy soil.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Bromus%20unioloides">Bromus unioloides</name> quickly growing grass, suitable for any kind of soil</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Maize to be sown on tolerably fertile ground; leaves &amp; stalks furnish good horsefeed, whilst the cob's in a green state are excellent eating</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Pumpkin,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Gourd</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Piemelon</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Rockmelon's 2 sorts</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">to be sown on rich land which should not be too dry</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Tomato seeds &amp;c will be sent by Mr Rule. White Clover seeds are already supplied. Dates Dr Murray I think has purchased. A large supply of seeds seems to be still at the Darling unused.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Ferd Mueller</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>11/12/61.</p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Bromus%20unioloides">Bromus unioloides</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Rumex%20vesicarius">Rumex vesicarius</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Sorghum%20nigrum">Sorghum nigrum</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Sorghum%20sacharatum">Sorghum sacharatum</name>
            </p>
         </div>
